The training of 1,056 community police constables for Kwara State commenced on Friday. Speaking at the flag-off ceremony of the training, Governor Abdulrahman Abdulrazaq, said the success of community policing rests on the society fully backing it. He asserted that the police was often a reflection of the society it serves. Governor Abdulrazaq commended security agencies for their hard work which has continued to keep Kwara mostly safe. He noted that the recent US travel advisory which exempted Kwara from the list of high-security risk states in the country testifies to the exceptional efforts of the police and other security agencies in the state to protect lives and properties. The governor urged them to continue to partner with the state government in that regard. He charged the new constables on discipline and commitment to duties which he described as the bedrock of policing job. “The people are integral to the success of the police. The people will give the information that the police will act on. These constables are products of the society and they will operate within the society that they understand,” the governor stated. ” This,” he added, ” Is the essence of community policing.” Governor Abdulrazaq also urged residents of the state to always volunteer timely information and support the police to burst criminal networks before they carry out their unlawful activities. The state police commissioner, Mohammed Lawal Bagega, on his part explained that the initiative was intended to enhance the fight against crime. Bagega stressed the significant role intelligence gathering plays in checking crimes, adding that ” The IGP, through the police service commission, wished to enhance the fight against crimes through intelligence-led policing. “Therefore, we need information and these people after graduation will be posted back to their respective communities,” he added.